1. Introduction

The motivation for this analysis is to help the Emil City Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) better target possible recipients of home repair tax credits. Until now HCD has been reaching out to homeowners at random to promote the credit program without any consideration for the characteristics of the homeowner, resulting in low program participation. To improve the success rate, I will use homeowner data from previous campaigns to account for the attributes that make homeowners more likely to join the program, and to create a predictive model that will allow HCD to use its limited resources to more effectively target possible program enrollees and maximize the economic benefits to the community.

2. Exploratory Analysis and Engineering New Features

I use various plots to visualize the relationships between the different features of each homeowner and the campaign during which they were contacted. I also engineered some new features. For continuous variables, I created new categorical ones that better accounted for variable distribution. For pdays, the number 999 was used as a dummy value to signify homeowners that hadnt been contacted yet. Given that this is the majority of homeowners, I created a new variable called pdays_cat that assigned one of two values: no for those with a 999 value, and yes for everyone else that had been contacted previously. I also noticed a significant rise in the density of homeowners that decline the program when they spend more than about $5175 on home repair (see Figure 2), and so I engineered a new binary variable called repair_cat to sort out those that spent at least that amount or spent less.

I also re-engineered some categorical variables to make them simpler and more intuitive. First, I reclassified the education variable (now called edu) down to 3 categories: Above high school, high school and below, and unknown. I also condensed the months into 4 seasons, as differences between seasons are more stark than between two consecutive months. Finally, I converted the job variable, which had several possible values, into a program-entrance average by job (a continuous value) called job.y.share, which conveys more information than a simple job descriptor.

housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(edu = ifelse((education =="university.degree" | education =="professional.course"), "aboveHS", ifelse(education == "unknown" | is.na(education), "unknown", "belowHS")))

housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(season = case_when(
    month == "dec" | month == "jan" | month == "feb" ~ "Winter",
    month == "mar" | month == "apr" | month == "may" ~ "Spring", 
    month == "jun" | month == "jul" | month == "aug" ~ "Summer",
    month == "sep" | month == "oct" | month == "nov" ~ "Fall"))

housing <- housing %>%  
  group_by(job) %>% 
  summarize(tot.y = sum(y_numeric), 
            n = n(), 
            job.y.share = 100*(tot.y/n)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-n, -tot.y) %>% 
  right_join(housing, .) 

housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(pdays_cat = ifelse(pdays == 999, "no", "yes"))

housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(repair_cat = ifelse(spent_on_repairs <= 5175, ">= 5175", "< 5175"))
housing %>%
  dplyr::select(y, age, campaign, previous, unemploy_rate, cons.price.idx, 
                cons.conf.idx, inflation_rate, spent_on_repairs, job.y.share) %>%
  gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
    ggplot(aes(y, value, fill=y)) + 
      geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat = "summary", fun = "mean") + 
      facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +
      scale_fill_manual(values = palette2) +
      labs(x="Entered the Program?", y="Value", 
           title = "Feature associations with the likelihood of entering the program",
           subtitle = "(continous outcomes)",
           caption = "Figure 1") +
      theme(legend.position = "none")

Figure 1 shows the mean value of different continuous variables for those that entered the program (yes) and those that didnt (no). This suggests a strong correlation between inflation_rate, previous, and unemploy_rate with the possibility that someone chooses to enter the program or not.

housing %>%
    dplyr::select(y, age, campaign, previous, unemploy_rate, cons.price.idx, 
                cons.conf.idx, spent_on_repairs, job.y.share, inflation_rate) %>%
    gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
    ggplot() + 
    geom_density(aes(value, color=y), fill = "transparent") + 
    facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +

    labs(title = "Feature distributions of entering (yes) vs. not entering (no)",
         subtitle = "(continous outcomes)",
         caption = "Figure 2")

Figure 2 re-visualizes the continuous variables and more clearly shows the distribution of variables based on program enrollment. The plot for conc.conf.idx, for example, shows that program enrollment is more responsive to the change in value more than the value itself, while program enrollment varies most around the extreme values of inflation_rate and spent_on_repairs (which I reclassified as explained above).

housing %>%
    dplyr::select(y, marital, edu, mortgage, contact, poutcome, taxLien, taxbill_in_phl, season,
                  pdays_cat, repair_cat) %>%
    gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
    count(Variable, value, y) %>%
      ggplot(., aes(value, n, fill = y)) +   
        geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat="identity") +
        facet_wrap(~Variable, scales="free") +
        scale_fill_manual(values = palette2, name = "Entered the program?") +

             title = "Feature associations with the likelihood of entering the program",
             subtitle = "Categorical features",
             caption = "Figure 3") +
        theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Figure 3 shows the count of those who did and did not enter the program based on different categorical variables. It is harder to find correlation in this plot as it uses counts, and overall a lot more people declined the program than entered it.

3. Running Logistic Regressions

The next step is to run logistic regressions to predict the probability that a homeowner will enroll in the program, based on a combination of the variables discussed above. The data is split 65/35 into a training and test set.

set.seed(3456)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(housing$y, p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)
housingTrain <- housing[ trainIndex,]
housingTest  <- housing[-trainIndex,]

First, I run a Kitchen Sink regression, utilizing all the original variables in the data set.

kitchenModel <- glm(y_numeric ~ .,
                  data=housingTrain %>% 
                    dplyr::select(-edu, -job.y.share, -season, -taxLien, -pdays_cat, -repair_cat, 
                                  -y),
                  family="binomial" (link="logit"))

3.2 Cross-Validation and ROC Curves

To further test the models I run a 100-fold cross-validation on both.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100, classProbs=TRUE, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary)

housing2 <- housing %>%
    mutate(y2 = ifelse(y == "no", "yes", "no"))

cvFit_kitchen <- train(y2 ~ .,
                  data=housing2 %>% 
                   na.omit() %>%
                    dplyr::select(-edu, -job.y.share, -season, -taxLien, -pdays_cat, -repair_cat, 
                                  -y_numeric, -y), 
                method="glm", family="binomial",
                metric="ROC", trControl = ctrl)

#cvFit_kitchen

cvFit_housing <- train(y2 ~ .,

Figures 11 and 12 show the results of the cross-validation. As seen in previous summaries, the results for both models are quite similar. Both show consistently high specificity and consistently low sensitivity (though there is some variation). The ROC for both models varies more considerably, though is clustered around 0.75, meaning both models are better predictors than a coin-flip in almost all folds.

ggplot(testProbs.kit, aes(d = as.numeric(Outcome), m = Probs)) +

Figures 13 and 14 show the ROC curves for the Kitchen Sink and Engineered models. Both are clearly better better than a coin-flip approach. The Engineered model has a larger Area Under the Curve (AUC), suggesting a slightly better fit.

4. Cost-Benefit Analysis

To quantify the potential value of my (Engineered) model, I do a cost/benefit analysis for each possible outcome.

If a true negative is predicted, than the cost/benefit is 0, as no marketing resources or credits are allocated to that person.

If a true positive is predicted, the cost is 2850 (for marketing outreach) + 0.25x5000 (the cost of the credit multiplied by 0.25, as it is assumed that only 25% of those that join the program will ultimately receive the $5000 credit). Since I represent a public authority concerned with the welfare of its citizens, I consider the expected home value premium to be a benefit of the program, and so for each positive prediction the benefit is (10,000 + 56,000)x.25 - the combined premium of the individual and neighboring home values, multiplied by .25 for the 25% that will ultimately receive the credit.

In the case of a false negative, the cost/benefit is 0, as these homeowners probably signed up or reasons unrelated to this campaign.

Finally, if there is a false positive the cost is just the cost of marketing to that person (2850), with no benefit.

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Benefit =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",(((-2850) - (1250)  + 16500)*Count ),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count, 0))))) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "We correctly predicted not entering the credit program.",
              "We correctly predicted entering the credit program.",
              "We predicted not entering the credit program and customer entered.",
              "We predicted entering the credit program and customer did not.")))

       caption = "Figure 15: Cost/Benefit Table by Confusion Metric") %>% kable_styling()

iterateThresholds <- function(data) {
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  while (x <= 1) {
  
  this_prediction <-
      testProbs %>%
      mutate(predOutcome = ifelse(Probs > x, 1, 0)) %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
     gather(Variable, Count) %>%
     mutate(Benefit =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",((-2850) * Count - (1250) * Count + 16500 * Count),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count, 0)))),
            Threshold = x)
  
  all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction, this_prediction)
  x <- x + .01
  }
return(all_prediction)
}
whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs)

5. Conclusion

Given that the Emil City HCD is currently just reaching out to homeowners at random, I recommend using my model over the status quo. While it is not perfect, it at least takes into account different attributes of the citys homeowners, and thus will probably pick out more interested homeowners than random selection. Furthermore the cost-benefit analysis shows it can create a net benefit to the city. In the future I would also do interviews with people that enroll in the program to get a sense of why they chose to do so, and use that information to better target new homeowners.

The model could be improved with a higher sensitivity. Right now my engineered model is not better than the Kitchen Sink regression in this regard. As seen in Figures 7 and 8, both models predict a large range of probabilities for homeowners who actually entered the program, with a skew below 0.5. Thus both models are going to struggle to accurately predict positive outcomes, especially with higher thresholds. On the other hand, the data appears to be quite good at predicting people who choose not to enroll. There may be factors that influence peoples decisions that arent reflected in the available data. There are also many more people that have declined the program in the past than those that have enrolled, possibly creating a bias in the data against those that enroll in the program. By abandoning the random selection and adopting my own model, the HCD may be able to at least reduce this imbalance, and in the future be able to create an even better model using less biased data.
